<li id="cite_note-WattQuote-114"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-WattQuote_114-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">"Having burst through the front, Budyonny's cavalry would devastate the enemy's rear – burning, killing and looting as they went. These Red cavalrymen inspired an almost numbing sense of fear in their opponents [...] the very names Budyonny and Cossack terrified the Ukrainian population, and they moved into a state of neutrality or even hostility toward Petliura and the Poles..."<br />
from Richard Watt, 1979. Bitter Glory: Poland and its fate 1918–1939. New York: Simon &amp; Schuster. <a href="Special_BookSources/9780671226251" class="internal mw-magiclink-isbn">ISBN 978-0-671-22625-1</a></span></li>
